        <h3>How to Read the Coordinates</h3>
        <p>
            Results are given in local (altazimuth) coordinates for easy spotting and for those who do not have an equatorial telescope mount.
            An altazimuth coordinate is composed of an altitude, or <i>angle of elevation</i>, and an azimuth, or <i>angle of rotation</i>.
            <br /><br />
            The altitude component tells you how high to look upward from your horizon. For example, your horizon on Earth is at an altitude of 0&deg;
            and the point located directly above you is at +90&deg;, which is known as your <i>zenith</i>. If you are tracking an object that has not
            yet risen above your horizon, then it will have a negative altitude ranging from 0&deg; to the point directly beneath you at -90&deg;,
            which is known as your <i>nadir</i>.
            <br /><br />
            The azimuth component tells you how far to look away from the direction of the geographic North Pole, traveling eastward from 0&deg; to 360&deg;.
            For example, an azimuth of 0&deg; is located directly north of your location; 90&deg; is to the east; 180&deg; is to the south; and 270&deg; is to the west.
            For observers located at or extremely close to either of Earth's poles, your azimuth will start from the Prime Meridian (longitude 0&deg;) and
            travel eastward to a longitude of +180&deg;, or westward to -180&deg;. Most of you will not be at these locations and will not have to
            worry about this.
            <br /><br />
            Finally, you may choose to display the results in either rounded form (45&deg;), decimal form (45.3&deg;), or in DMS form (45&deg;18&prime;0&Prime;).
            The DMS form, or Degrees-Minutes-Seconds, may be helpful for those who are using specialized equipment, or for those who prefer this notation.
        </p>
    </article>

